WEBVTT

00:00:00.102 --> 00:00:02.355
A green checkmark is one of the most
comforting

00:00:02.381 --> 00:00:07.331
shapes in software It says the build
passed The

00:00:07.344 --> 00:00:12.135
tests passed The robot is happy And when
you are

00:00:12.161 --> 00:00:14.531
tired it is easy to read that as a bigger

00:00:14.557 --> 00:00:19.258
sentence This is safe to merge But a green
check

00:00:19.271 --> 00:00:22.812
usually means something narrower It means
this

00:00:22.826 --> 00:00:25.026
check passed on this version under these

00:00:25.039 --> 00:00:30.391
conditions That is useful evidence It is
not a verdict

00:00:31.436 --> 00:00:33.780
Here are three questions that keep the
signal in

00:00:33.806 --> 00:00:38.131
its lane Fresh base Right diff

00:00:39.042 --> 00:00:40.240
Uncovered risk

00:00:41.270 --> 00:00:44.957
First Fresh base Did the check run against
the

00:00:44.970 --> 00:00:48.525
target you are about to merge or deploy
into In

00:00:48.538 --> 00:00:51.194
a fast-moving repo the target branch can
move

00:00:51.220 --> 00:00:54.293
while a pull request waits The check may
have

00:00:54.319 --> 00:00:57.652
been true when main looked one way Then
other

00:00:57.678 --> 00:01:02.158
work lands The surrounding file changes A

00:01:02.184 --> 00:01:05.986
validator appears A slot that was empty
becomes

00:01:06.012 --> 00:01:10.829
occupied The old check is not useless But
it is

00:01:10.842 --> 00:01:14.671
dated evidence In one exploratory AI
Village

00:01:14.697 --> 00:01:17.223
pull-request study local git
reconstruction

00:01:17.249 --> 00:01:20.751
found six hundred and ten pull requests
One

00:01:20.777 --> 00:01:23.121
hundred forty-four pull-request heads were
not

00:01:23.134 --> 00:01:26.689
descendants of their recorded base That
does not

00:01:26.715 --> 00:01:30.100
prove those branches were unsafe It does
mean

00:01:30.126 --> 00:01:32.691
the base relationship was a useful place
to look

00:01:33.603 --> 00:01:38.147
Green on an old base is not bad evidence
It is old evidence

00:01:39.158 --> 00:01:42.626
Second Right diff Did the check inspect
the

00:01:42.650 --> 00:01:46.335
exact change that will land A file list is
not

00:01:46.348 --> 00:01:49.915
the same as the current merge diff A
preview you

00:01:49.928 --> 00:01:52.168
remember is not the same as the change
that will

00:01:52.194 --> 00:01:55.931
ship In the same study's case appendix one
pull

00:01:55.957 --> 00:01:58.457
request is described as mechanically
mergeable

00:01:58.483 --> 00:02:01.595
with passing checks But a reviewer noted
that

00:02:01.608 --> 00:02:03.576
its diff inserted new entries before an

00:02:03.600 --> 00:02:06.074
already-merged tail shifting the intended

00:02:06.100 --> 00:02:08.105
numbering instead of appending after
current

00:02:08.132 --> 00:02:11.400
main The issue was not simply whether the
code

00:02:11.426 --> 00:02:14.342
could parse The issue was whether the
checked

00:02:14.368 --> 00:02:17.702
change matched the real review question So
do

00:02:17.715 --> 00:02:21.191
not only ask whether a check passed Ask
what

00:02:21.217 --> 00:02:22.780
diff the check was attached to

00:02:23.788 --> 00:02:27.514
Third Uncovered risk What important
failure

00:02:27.540 --> 00:02:29.806
could still happen even if the check
result is

00:02:29.832 --> 00:02:33.113
correct Some failures are easy for generic

00:02:33.139 --> 00:02:35.823
automation to see the file does not
compile the

00:02:35.847 --> 00:02:38.662
unit test fails a required command exits
with an

00:02:38.686 --> 00:02:43.113
error Other failures are about meaning Did
this

00:02:43.126 --> 00:02:46.446
remove recent work Did it preserve the
source

00:02:46.472 --> 00:02:49.767
layout the application expects Did it
change

00:02:49.780 --> 00:02:52.855
permissions ordering user-visible wording
or a

00:02:52.840 --> 00:02:56.420
hidden invariant The most useful question
is not

00:02:56.616 --> 00:03:00.066
Did the robot approve It is What would
still

00:03:00.092 --> 00:03:01.746
worry me if the robot is right

00:03:02.764 --> 00:03:06.633
This is also the caveat A stale branch is
not

00:03:06.659 --> 00:03:10.488
automatically unsafe A large deletion
count is

00:03:10.514 --> 00:03:14.290
not automatically bad And a passing check
is not

00:03:14.316 --> 00:03:18.990
automatically enough Each of those is a
signal not a verdict

00:03:20.020 --> 00:03:22.325
So before you treat a green check as
approval

00:03:22.520 --> 00:03:26.051
ask Fresh base did the check run against
the

00:03:26.064 --> 00:03:29.592
target I am about to merge or deploy into
Right

00:03:29.619 --> 00:03:32.236
diff did it inspect the exact change that
will

00:03:32.262 --> 00:03:36.155
land Uncovered risk what important failure
could

00:03:36.181 --> 00:03:38.264
still happen even if this check result is

00:03:38.277 --> 00:03:41.845
correct If you are using an AI assistant
during

00:03:41.858 --> 00:03:45.022
review you can ask it the same thing What

00:03:45.048 --> 00:03:47.717
version base branch and diff did this
check run

00:03:47.744 --> 00:03:51.650
on What files behaviors or risks did it
not

00:03:51.663 --> 00:03:55.217
inspect What human decision remains even
if the

00:03:55.230 --> 00:03:58.590
check result is correct That prompt will
not

00:03:58.603 --> 00:04:02.210
make the decision safe by itself But it
can slow

00:04:02.223 --> 00:04:04.579
the moment down just enough to keep the
evidence

00:04:04.606 --> 00:04:09.163
visible Keep the green check It is useful

00:04:10.074 --> 00:04:13.564
Just read it like a receipt What version
did it

00:04:13.577 --> 00:04:18.473
check What diff did it inspect What risk
did it

00:04:18.486 --> 00:04:21.845
leave uncovered Let the green check speed
up the

00:04:21.858 --> 00:04:25.283
review Do not let it replace the question
